3. What endpoint was vulnerable to SQL injection?
Let's go back and look again, this time keeping an eye out for anything that looks like it might be SQL.
And here we are!

::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:29:15 +0000] "GET /rest/products/search?q=%28SELECT%20%28CASE%20WHEN%20%288195%3D8761%29%20THEN%201%20ELSE%20%28SELECT%208761%20UNION%20SELECT%203788%29%20END%29%29 HTTP/1.1" 200 30 "-" "sqlmap/1.5.2#stable (http://sqlmap.org)"

(There was a bit of SQL in the previous few logs, but this one, if you can parse out the text being used, has a full SELECT statement.)


4. What parameter was used for the SQL injection?
Let's take one of these lines as an example:

::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:29:15 +0000] "GET /rest/products/search?q=1%27cjocta%3C%27%22%3ETuFsMe HTTP/1.1" 500 - "-" "sqlmap/1.5.2#stable (http://sqlmap.org)"

See the "search?q="? That means that you are using the q search box to run your query. Thus, q is the parameter being exploited.


5. What endpoint did the attacker try to use to retrieve files? (Include the /)
If we look towards the end, we see these lines:

::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:34:40 +0000] "GET /ftp/www-data.bak HTTP/1.1" 403 300 "-" "Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64; rv:78.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/78.0"
::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:34:43 +0000] "GET /ftp/coupons_2013.md.bak HTTP/1.1" 403 78965 "-" ""Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64; rv:78.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/78.0"

This signals the attacker trying to GET (or download) the files at /ftp/www-data.bak and /ftp/coupons_2013.md.bak. Therefore, the endpoint being attacked is the /ftp endpoint.


