7. Was their brute-force attack successful? If so, what is the timestamp of the successful login? (Yay/Nay, 11/Apr/2021:09:xx:xx +0000)
There's one lone log where the HTTP code given is 200, which means "OK" (rather than code 401 or 500, which mean unauthorized and internal server error, respectively).

::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:16:31 +0000] "POST /rest/user/login HTTP/1.0" 200 831 "-" "Mozilla/5.0 (Hydra)"

Time stamp is right there for all to see in the 4th field, so: Yay, 11/Apr/2021:09:16:31 +0000.


8. What user information was the attacker able to retrieve from the endpoint vulnerable to SQL injection?
If we take a look at the last SQL statement inserted:

::ffff:192.168.10.5 - - [11/Apr/2021:09:32:51 +0000] "GET /rest/products/search?q=qwert%27))%20UNION%20SELECT%20id,%20email,%20password,%20%274%27,%20%275%27,%20%276%27,%20%277%27,%20%278%27,%20%279%27%20FROM%20Users-- HTTP/1.1" 200 3742 "-" "curl/7.74.0"

We can decipher this to mean "UNION SELECT id, email, password." Id isn't relevant here, as it doesn't give us any information to exploit. Therefore, the answer they're looking for is simply email and password.


